      <h3 class="header-one">Common Causes of Falls</h3>
      <p>Falls can result from a variety of factors including environmental hazards, physical conditions, and even certain medications. Environmental hazards such as wet floors, poor lighting, and clutter can significantly increase the risk of falls. Physical conditions like muscle weakness, balance issues, and vision problems also play a major role.</p>
      <h3>Impact of Falls</h3>
      <p>Falls can lead to serious injuries, particularly among older adults. These injuries include fractures, head injuries, and sometimes, long-term disability. The psychological impact, such as fear of falling, can also reduce an individual's quality of life by limiting their activities and social interactions.</p>
      <h3>Prevention Strategies</h3>
      <p>Preventing falls involves addressing the various risk factors. Regular exercise to improve strength and balance, proper home modifications to eliminate hazards, and regular health check-ups to manage medical conditions are essential. Additionally, using assistive devices and wearing proper footwear can further reduce the risk.</p>
      <h3>Emergency Response</h3>
      <p>Knowing how to respond in case of a fall is crucial. Immediate actions such as seeking medical help, administering first aid, and understanding how to safely assist a fallen person can make a significant difference in the outcome of the incident. Education and preparedness are key components of an effective response plan.</p>
